- [A] causes [C]
- [B] causes [C]
- [A] and [B] are not causally related

recycled to `(T, F, F, NA, T, F)` and `x` is indexed as `x[c(T, F, F, NA, T, F)]`. Since position `1` and `5` are `TRUE`, those will be returned, the ones with `FALSE` will not be returned and the position which has `NA` will return #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:11082021220005]
`NA`. So the output will be `1 NA 5`. #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:11082021220005]

and the ones with `FALSE` are dropped. If in case your logical vector is of smaller length, the elements are recycled to match the corresponding length. So in the above example: `y` is of length 4, so when used as `x[y]`, `y` gets #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:11082021220005]

# courtesy @hadleywickham 

# define vars
`*tmp*` <- "I exist"
x <- 1

# *tmp* exists

# use a replacement function
names(x) <- "I have a name"

# *tmp* vanishes
